; Drop-in override example: anti-abuse tunables.
;
; Copy to /etc/systemd/system/katpool-bridge.service.d/anti-abuse.conf
; (drop the `.example` suffix), edit the values, then run:
;
;   sudo systemctl daemon-reload
;   sudo systemctl restart katpool-bridge
;
; Defaults if unset (see `bridge/src/anti_abuse.rs`):
;
;   KATPOOL_ANTI_ABUSE_MAX_CONN_PER_IP=256
;   KATPOOL_ANTI_ABUSE_MAX_TRACKED_IPS=65536
;   KATPOOL_ANTI_ABUSE_FRAME_RATE_PER_SEC=100
;   KATPOOL_ANTI_ABUSE_FRAME_BURST=200
;
; Tuning notes:
;
; - max_conn_per_ip: legitimate large farms can host hundreds of ASICs
;   behind a single NAT. Set this to "worst case farm size × 1.5".
; - max_tracked_ips: protects HashMap memory under DDoS. Each entry is
;   ~64 bytes; 65,536 → ~4 MiB worst case.
; - frame_rate_per_sec: typical stratum traffic is 1-5 frames/sec/ASIC.
;   100 leaves >20× headroom while still catching obvious floods.
; - frame_burst: maximum legal short-term burst. Should be ≥ the largest
;   batch a legitimate miner might send (mining.subscribe + authorize +
;   set_difficulty + the first few submits ≈ 5-10 frames).
;
; Malformed values fail-fast at start-up (the unit will report
; "anti-abuse config: environment variable …" in journalctl and exit
; non-zero), so an operator typo never silently degrades protection.

[Service]
Environment=KATPOOL_ANTI_ABUSE_MAX_CONN_PER_IP=256
Environment=KATPOOL_ANTI_ABUSE_MAX_TRACKED_IPS=65536
Environment=KATPOOL_ANTI_ABUSE_FRAME_RATE_PER_SEC=100
Environment=KATPOOL_ANTI_ABUSE_FRAME_BURST=200
